<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> It's all about timing<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.54)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9105'>Andrew "Lumpy" Salisbury</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9105&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 4, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> We&#39;ve all been told about selecting the correct sites for our decks, not just shadow or fellowship. We&#39;ve all been made aware of cycling through our deck fast enough to get the cards we want when we need them. What do these two things have in common? Timing!<br>
<br>
I can hear you asking, &quot;What are you on about looney?&quot;. Fair enough. Looney is as looney does, but I think there&#39;s a valid point to be found here, and I&#39;ll try my darndest to make it obvious.<br>
<br>
Firstly, lets take a look again at site control. If you win the bid and opt to go second then you probably know something the opponent doesn&#39;t, and if he/she/it doesn&#39;t catch on to this you&#39;re already a leg up! When I bid to go second it means either a) I have no site control cards like Pathfinder, Nelya, or Thrors Map and like my path the way I set it, or b) I want more control over where you&#39;re going instead of you picking the path. The choice to go second could ruin your gameplan if you&#39;re unprepared, especially if you&#39;ve got turtles for companions, but this issue of timing is something you SHOULD prepare for. You&#39;ve also probably noticed that a lot of people are running around designing decks hinging on the fact that they have to go first, but what if you&#39;re opponent WANTS you to go first? Now there&#39;s food for thought.<br>
<br>
Secondly, we should examine what to do if you are going second. If you&#39;re going second deliberately then I suggest working on a redundancy plan. If you&#39;re laying out the smack with an Isengard culture shadow deck think about including some spells to slow down the fellowship. Most of these weather conditions either mean that the minions about don&#39;t want you to amp up and beat them down, or are designed to stop you in your tracks. Stopping a leading fellowship in its tracks is quite handy, and if you can do it more than once then not only can you keep up with them but instead put yourselves in pole position. Sounds tempting doesn&#39;t it? Unfortunately for you there&#39;s nothing you can do about the opponent selecting the sites with Thrors Map except look to another culture to get rid of it for you - not going to happen.<br>
If you&#39;re dividing and conquering with Nazgul, then as far as I can tell you WANT them to go second. By them heading off first you can cycle through some cards a little quicker (quite tricky to do with the Nazgul) and not only prep yourself for a handy fellowship but can play uber-sites-of-doom-from-Nam like the Fords of Bruinen or even Weatherhills or Weathertop. Chances are they&#39;re not quite setup early on to start selecting their own sites to play so you don&#39;t have to worry about that, instead worry about getting enough minions down to lay into their guys and allow you to draw enough cards for your fellowship phase.<br>
Setting up the gauntlet in Moria? Wonderful, going second can really help you here as the Moria sites can really assist different Moria decks. Heading out with a weapon deck? The Stairway or Mithril Mine can really hurt them here. Dont like Dwarves? Dwarrowdelf chamber assists you here. By the time they get to your minions in waiting you should&#39;ve cycled through enough weapons to discard pile to load up your hand with Moria minions all ready to leap out of your hands, arm up, and swarm the fellowship to its ruin.<br>
In all of these situations it should be becoming obvious what I&#39;m getting at. Getting cards in and out of hands according to the right schedule your playing to. Each deck requires different timing and trying to cycle through your deck too late in a Ringwraith culture will cost you the game, or pushing out enough minions from Moria early on to slow them down won&#39;t work - they&#39;re too squishy to do much that early on and you&#39;ll have bigger troubles getting them back out of your discard pile. It&#39;s all about timing, timing, and timing.<br>
<br>
Finally, the remaining section of the game I haven&#39;t referred to with timing - combat. During the skirmish phase, you have to get them in the right order. Got more than one hobbit in a combat and only one dagger strike in hand? Choose the combat you&#39;re most likely to win first, so you probably won&#39;t have to use this precious card that could save a life or a bounder exertion. Bow of the Galadhrim and thinking of legging it? Choose another winning combat against a multiple wound creature - preferably fierce - and win, then do your battle with the Bow of the Galadhrim wearer, win their and get rid of that nasty creature that could come back and hurt you. They don&#39;t come back to punch you one when they&#39;re dead. Also be careful of what you&#39;re up against. A Moria deck can have a very handy setup in regards to weapons. If you kill a pathetic runner who was armed with a scimitar, Plundered Armories can bounce that back to another minion that you didn&#39;t count on being armed originally. When used in conjunction with Goblin Armory they&#39;ll be adding twilight (handy to have when you&#39;re Moria and have a Guard Commander about) and drawing cards from the scimitar itself. That one card could be your ruin (Unfamiliar Territory, Drums in the Deep etc). Be careful against Moria decks they can really change their plans to suit the situation, you can&#39;t. Lastly in the skirmish section of my diatribe, adding twilight. Be careful adding twilight as a lot of cultures require twilight in combat. A fine example of this is the Isengard culture, who can use many things that require twilight in combat ie. Uruk Slayer, Uruk-Hai Rampage, Lurtzs Battlecry etc. If you hamstring your opponent by not providing twilight at the correct time for him then you can change a horribly lost battle to won where the battle scars are something to be proud of. Above all it seems, take a note of what&#39;s out, if you have a good outlook on what cards are on the table, and you know what they all do then any issues regarding timing and when to play what should be elementary.<br>
<br>
In summary, be careful. By taking account of all the things out there that are trying to kill you, you can make things much easier for yourself by doing things in the correct order and at the right times. It&#39;s critical to get the right sites out at the right time, and it&#39;s just as important not to get your companions killed simply because you did this combat first and not that one, and above all - get yourself into the right position in the order of play. With all these skills under your belt you&#39;ll be a Middle Earth champ faster than you can say &quot;I wish there was a card for Sauron himself&quot;. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3255&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
